EASYWAY: On UBUNTU systems use the installation script:
  $sudo sh install.sh
  set the paths in your .bashrc (sudo gedit ~/.bashrc):
	LD_LIBRARY_PATH=$LD_LIBRARY_PATH:/usr/local/lib:
	export LD_LIBRARY_PATH
	export PYTHONPATH="${PYTHONPATH}:/location of lightfieldoperators/"
	export PYTHONPATH="${PYTHONPATH}:/location of lightfieldoperators/lazyflow/"

  run in shell: $viewLF /location/of/a/lightfield.h5
  or from python: import LFLib.Viewer.viewer as viewer
		viewer.show("here filename or lightfield instance")

OTHERWISE manually install:

Dependencies:

LIBRARIES:
  libqt4-dev
  libopenexr-dev
  libhdf5-serial-dev
  libfftw3-dev
  doxygen
  libboost-all-dev
  libblas-dev
  liblapack-dev
  gfortran


PYTHON (2.7):
  python-numpy (1.5.1)
  python-scipy (0.9.0)
  python-matplotlib (1.0.1)
  python-h5py (2.0.0)
  python-qt4 (4.8.5)
  python-qt4-gl
  python-qt4-dev
  pyqt4-dev-tools
  python-sphinx
  cython (0.16)
  OpenEXR (1.2.0)
  

OTHERS:
  cmake
  vigra see subdirectory ./LFLib/vigra
  lazyflow see subdirectory ./LFLib/lazyflow



Build Vigra:

  Dependencies for vigra:
  libjpeg, libtiff, libpng, OpenEXR for reading and writing JPEG, TIFF, PNG, and EXR images respectively.
  HDF5 for reading and writing HDF5 files (storage of MultiArray and RandomForest).
  libfftw for fast Fourier transforms.
  doxygen and Python to generate C++ documentation.
  Python, boost_python, and numpy to compile and run vigranumpy (the VIGRA Python bindings).
  sphinx to generate vigranumpy documentation.
  nosetests to execute the vigranumpy test suite.

    > mkdir \<vigra_build_path\>       
    > cd \<vigra_build_path\>       
    > cmake [options] \<vigra_source_path\>
    > make          # build (Linux/Unix and MinGW only)
    > make check    # compile and run tests (optional, Linux/Unix and MinGW only)
    > make doc      # generate documentation (Linux/Unix and MinGW only)
    > make install  # install (Linux/Unix and MinGW only)
    > make examples # build examples (optional, Linux/Unix and MinGW only)


Build lazyflow:

  Dependencies for lazyflow:
  greenlet,psutil,vigra
	

    > run $easy_install psutil greenlet       
    > cd lightfieldoperators/LFLib/lazyflow>       
    > python setup.py build
    > sudo python setup.py install


after all run $sudo sh lightfieldoperators/LFLib/setup.sh

ensure to set all environment variables (see top of the page)

run in shell: $viewLF /location/of/a/lightfield.h5
or from python: import LFLib.Viewer.viewer as viewer
		viewer.show("here filename or lightfield instance")



